media.description: Clean the PCB with ammonia and a green scrubby as usual.
media.title: IMG_0999.JPG

media.description:
Mixed up a 3:8 concoction of acetone and denatured alcohol per the internet. 
*Note the scale on the plastic syringe, this is about the last time it will be seen as the acetone takes the ink right off the plastic.
media.title: IMG_1001.JPG

media.description: Moistened the surface with the solution, placed the printed pattern face down, added more solution and pressure.
media.title: IMG_1002.JPG

media.description: Soaking in water to remove the paper.
media.title: IMG_1003.JPG

media.description:
Voila!

It didn't work.  Not even close.
media.title: IMG_1004.JPG

media.description:
So, let's just try pure acetone.
I taped the pattern to the board, and soaked it from behind with acetone.  I hadn't considered what the acetone would do to the adhesive, which is dissolve it and make it a sticky mess.
media.title: IMG_1005.JPG

media.description: After several soakings of the paper with acetone alternating with pressure I'm soaking it to remove the paper.  Interestingly the paper does not want to wet.
media.title: IMG_1006.JPG

media.description: Some of the toner transferred so there is some truth to this, but it is not usable as a resist.  This is standard copy paper, perhaps I need to print on different paper like magazine or glossy.
media.title: IMG_1007.JPG

media.description: There's hope but that's about it for now.
media.title: IMG_1008.JPG
